      { label: 'Riesling', text: 'Germany\'s most celebrated grape ‚Äî from bone-dry (<em>trocken</em>) to lusciously sweet (<em>Sp√§tlese</em>, <em>Auslese</em>). The Mosel, Rheingau, and Pfalz produce world-class Riesling. A bottle runs <strong>‚Ç¨8‚Äì25</strong> at a wine shop and <strong>‚Ç¨5‚Äì10 per glass</strong> at a Weinstube. Look for producers like <strong>Dr. Loosen</strong>, <strong>Schloss Johannisberg</strong>, or <strong>D√∂nnhoff</strong>. The mineral, petrol-tinged dry Rieslings of the Rheingau are legendary.' },
      { label: 'Sp√§tburgunder (Pinot Noir)', text: 'Germany\'s finest red ‚Äî elegant, nuanced, with notes of cherry, raspberry, and earth. The Ahr Valley, Baden, and Pfalz produce outstanding examples. Bottles start at <strong>‚Ç¨10‚Äì30</strong>. By-the-glass at a wine bar, expect <strong>‚Ç¨6‚Äì12</strong>. Often lighter than French Burgundy but equally complex. Try <strong>Meyer-N√§kel</strong>, <strong>Friedrich Becker</strong>, or <strong>Bernhard Huber</strong> for world-class Sp√§tburgunder.' },
      { label: 'Gew√ºrztraminer', text: 'An aromatic, intensely floral white from Pfalz and Baden ‚Äî lychee, rose petal, and spice notes. Bold and distinctive. A bottle runs <strong>‚Ç¨8‚Äì18</strong>. Perfect with Asian-inspired dishes and spicy food. Germany\'s version is often drier and more refined than Alsatian examples. A glass of chilled Gew√ºrztraminer on a terrace along the Rhine is pure pleasure.' },
      { label: 'Silvaner & M√ºller-Thurgau', text: 'Franconia\'s signature grapes ‚Äî Silvaner is earthy, herbal, and mineral-driven, served in the distinctive round <em>Bocksbeutel</em> bottle. <strong>‚Ç¨6‚Äì15</strong> per bottle. M√ºller-Thurgau is lighter, floral, and easy-drinking ‚Äî the everyday white of Germany. Both pair beautifully with Franconian cuisine ‚Äî sausages, freshwater fish, and hearty soups.' },
      { label: 'Wine Regions & Weinstube Culture', text: 'Germany has 13 official wine regions. The <strong>Mosel</strong> has steep slate vineyards along the river. The <strong>Rheingau</strong> produces aristocratic Rieslings. The <strong>Pfalz</strong> is the warmest and most productive. <strong>Franconia</strong> (around W√ºrzburg) specializes in dry Silvaner. A <em>Weinstube</em> (wine tavern) is the heart of German wine culture ‚Äî cozy, wood-paneled, serving local wines by the glass with seasonal dishes. Expect <strong>‚Ç¨3‚Äì8</strong> per glass.' },
