    icon: 'üç∫',
    title: 'Beer Culture',
    gradient: 'linear-gradient(135deg, #E8654A 0%, #FB923C 100%)',
    items: [
      { label: 'Pilsner & Helles', text: 'The everyday beers of Germany. <strong>Pilsner</strong> (hoppy, crisp, bitter) dominates the north ‚Äî <strong>Jever</strong>, <strong>Bitburger</strong>, <strong>Warsteiner</strong>. <strong>Helles</strong> (malty, smooth, golden) rules Bavaria ‚Äî <strong>Augustiner</strong>, <strong>Paulaner</strong>, <strong>Spaten</strong>. A half-liter (<em>Halbe</em>) costs <strong>‚Ç¨3‚Äì5</strong> at a beer garden, <strong>‚Ç¨4‚Äì7</strong> at a restaurant. Augustiner Helles on draft at a Munich beer garden is one of Germany\'s great pleasures.' },
      { label: 'Wei√übier (Wheat Beer)', text: 'Bavaria\'s signature style ‚Äî cloudy, fruity, with banana and clove notes from the yeast. Served in tall, curved glasses. <strong>Weihenstephan</strong> (the world\'s oldest brewery, since 1040), <strong>Erdinger</strong>, and <strong>Schneider</strong> are the classic brands. A half-liter runs <strong>‚Ç¨3.50‚Äì6</strong>. Traditionally a morning beer ‚Äî Bavarians drink <em>Wei√üwurst-Fr√ºhst√ºck</em> (white sausage breakfast) with Wei√übier before noon. It\'s not a tourist gimmick; locals genuinely do this.' },
      { label: 'K√∂lsch & Altbier', text: '<strong>K√∂lsch</strong> ‚Äî Cologne\'s protected pale ale, served in small 0.2L glasses (<em>Stangen</em>) from a circular tray (<em>Kranz</em>). The waiter keeps bringing rounds until you cover your glass with a coaster. <strong>‚Ç¨1.50‚Äì2.50</strong> per glass. Try <strong>Fr√ºh</strong>, <strong>Gaffel</strong>, or <strong>Reissdorf</strong>. <strong>Altbier</strong> is D√ºsseldorf\'s answer ‚Äî copper-colored, malty, bitter. There\'s a legendary rivalry between the two cities over which is better.' },
